SIMPLE: supplement
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supplement
<hw>Sup"ple*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>suppl⟦eacute⟧ment</ets>, L. <ets>supplementum</ets>, fr.
<ets>supplere</ets> to fill up. See <er>Supply</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which supplies a deficiency, or
meets a want; a store; a supply.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which fills up, completes, or makes an addition
to, something already organized, arranged, or set apart; specifically, a
part added to, or issued as a continuation of, a book or paper, to make
good its deficiencies or correct its errors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Trig.)</fld> <def>The number of degrees which, if
added to a specified arc, make it 180⟦deg⟧; the quantity by which an arc
or an angle falls short of 180 degrees, or an arc falls short of a
semicircle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Appendix.</syn> -- <usage><er>Appendix</er>,
<er>Supplement</er>. An <xex>appendix</xex> is that which is appended to
something, but is not essential to its completeness; a
<xex>supplement</xex> is that which supplements, or serves to complete
or make perfect, that to which it is added.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supplement</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Supplement
<hw>Sup"ple*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Supplemented</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Supplementing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To fill up or supply by
addition; to add something to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Causes of one kind must be <qex>supplemented</qex> by bringing to
bear upon them a causation of another kind.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supplementary</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Supplemental</ent>⟦br⟧
